wb_means = c()
wb_sd = c()
for(i in 1 : 8){
  all_length = wblake$Length
  subgroup = all_length[wblake == i]
  wb_means[i] = mean(subgroup)
  wb_sd[i] = sd(subgroup)
}
ages = c(1 : 8)
#(a)
wb_means
## [1]  98.34211 124.84722 152.56383 193.80000 221.72059 252.59770 269.86885
## [8] 306.25000
plot(ages, wb_means)

From the plot, because we can see that the 8 points are approximately on a stright line, then I would say there is a evidence for a linear relationship between mean Length and Age.

#(b)
wb_sd
## [1] 28.42941 26.40618 20.28960 29.45263 31.39581 33.24275 29.48529 42.46077
plot(ages, wb_sd)

From the plot, because we can see that 8 points are not on a horizontal line, then I would say the variance does not appear constant across the different age population.

Based on the result, we get the t-value for the null hypothesis test that the slope is 0: 19.97. Conclusion: at confident level alpha = 0.01, we have significant evidence to show that the null hypothesis, “the slope is zero”, is false.

#(g)
confidenceEllipse(lm.1, grid=TRUE, xlab="Intercept", ylab="Slope",                   
                        main="99% confidence region and intervals", levels = 0.99)
abline(h=confint(lm.1,level=.99)[2,1],lty=2,lwd=2,col="red") 
abline(h=confint(lm.1,level=.99)[2,2],lty=2,lwd=2,col="red") 
abline(v=confint(lm.1,level=.99)[1,1],lty=2,lwd=2,col="red") 
abline(v=confint(lm.1,level=.99)[1,2],lty=2,lwd=2,col="red")
points(1.1, -.2,col="red",lwd=3)

Because the point (1.1, -0.2) is in the 1% confidence ellipse, I would not rejectt he hypothesis (β0, β1)T = (1.1, −.2) at the 1% level.
